Heil wants to examine other sectors after meat industry
The corona crisis brought the conditions in parts of the meat industry back to light.
Legislative tightening is imminent.
But are they legal - and will they remain so?
Federal Labour Minister Hubertus Heil (SPD) wants to examine other sectors following the now planned strict regulations against abuses in the meat industry.
"We will look at industry by industry and then take appropriate measures for the respective industry if necessary," Heil told the German Press Agency in Berlin.
Germany's employers are already warning against restricting work contracts in general.
Following the massive corona outbreak at meat giant Tönnies in North Rhine-Westphalia, the Federal Cabinet wants to pass a Heil law this Wednesday.
Large slaughterhouses should no longer be allowed to use external personnel for slaughtering, cutting and meat processing.
To this end, the use of contract and temporary workers is to be banned there.
Employer President Ingo Kramer told the dpa: "Hands off a general restriction of work contracts and temporary employment, if you do not want to completely strangle the economy.".
Contracts for work are, for example, the basis for creating added value for customers in large areas of the trades, the construction industry and plant engineering.
"The misdeeds of individuals cannot destroy such an important instrument.".
Heil assured: "My goal is not to ban contracts for works everywhere in the German economy.".
Work contracts make sense.
"If an industrial company commissions a tradesman to install a security system, this is a completely normal work contract.".
The German meat industry considers a ban on work contracts and temporary work in its sector alone to be unconstitutional.
According to a statement on the draft law, the "Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung" (Saturday) reports that it is inexplicable why different labour laws should apply to portioning and packaging of cheese in the future than to sausage.
A ban would increase the consumer price by 10 to 20 percent per kilo and product.
According to the results of an audit by the North Rhine-Westphalia Occupational Safety and Health Administration, many Eastern European employees from contract companies worked 16 hours a day.
They often had no break.
Salary was withheld for protective equipment or rent.
It was also found that the situation with regard to the accommodation of employees was often miserable.
Heil said that a relatively harsh law had already come into force for the meat industry in 2017.
However, these have been circumvented by "tricky constructions.".
"Now we have to clean up.".
The politician announced: "The Occupational Health and Safety Act, which we want to pass in the cabinet at the end of July, also includes measures that do not only affect the meat industry - for example, higher inspection rates for occupational health and safety or clear criteria for communal accommodation.".
The draft presented to the dpa includes amendments to the Act on Safeguarding Employee Rights in the Meat Industry and the Occupational Safety and Health Act.
Brandenburg's Consumer Protection Minister Ursula Nonnemacher (Greens) considers more intensive controls necessary.
"I would like us to be able to carry out even more checks in many supervisory areas: food controls, animal protection, all kinds of things, including animal transport," said Nonnemacher on Sunday in the RBB programme "Brandenburg aktuell.".
But more personnel positions are also needed for more controls.
