Baden-Württemberg: More than 250 illegal car races recorded
Stuttgart - Despite all the threatened penalties and court verdicts, motorists continue to step on the gas in countless illegal races on the roads of Baden-Württemberg: Last year and the first four months of this year, the police in the southwest have already registered more than 250 illegal car races.
Although there are no comparative figures for the previous years, the speeders are increasingly making work for the judicial authorities: In 2018, the public prosecutors between Konstanz and Mannheim conducted a total of 155 investigations into illegal races, a year later there were already 252 and in the current year up to the beginning of June already 151.
The races were less about organized events, as can be seen from the reply of the Ministry of the Interior to a request from the SPD.
In most cases, the drivers spontaneously competed against each other or fled from the police - this is also reported as an illegal race.
At the wheel were mainly German men between the ages of 18 and 60.
113 fines - 15 times imprisonment
Only in comparatively few cases are the speeders caught and asked to pay: According to the Ministry of the Interior, a total of 113 fines and 15 prison sentences have been imposed since 2018.
However, there is no indication that the number of illegal car races is actually increasing.
Rather, because of the numerous tragic accidents and lawsuits of recent years, other drivers reacted more sensitively than before and reported more frequently, a ministry spokesman said.
Highway 8 is particularly popular with speeders. Again and again, drivers slow down the traffic there in order to make room for themselves and use the free distance for a race.
Last August, a dozen drivers were caught near Kirchheim unter Teck, three months earlier there were even 18 drivers on the A8 near Merklingen.
A81 is most popular "racetrack"
The police even register more races on the A81 than on any other federal highway.
A speed limit is being set to try to slow down the speeders on the particularly affected section between Engen and Geisingen.
The mostly high-priced and pimped-up sports and luxury cars often have Swiss license plates, because the drivers avoid racing in Germany because of the high penalties for driving too fast and racing cars in the neighboring country.
For the SPD, the speed limit must not be reduced to a few routes: "With a general speed limit of 130 kilometers per hour, we would get rid of this problem on motorways," says Martin Rivoir, the transport expert of the SPD parliamentary group.
"The inhibition threshold for speeders would be significantly higher if you were not allowed to travel legally here and there at 200 kilometres per hour and more.".
Rivoir thinks less of education or image campaigns: "Anyone who defies all rules in such a way and puts not only their own lives, but also the lives of other road users at risk, is hardly reachable with reason.".
ADAC calls for stronger police crackdown
For the ADAC, however, this is not enough: "We assume that speeders will not be deterred by the speed limits," says Holger Bach, Head of Transport and Environment at the ADAC Württemberg.
It calls for additional and also tougher controls on the affected routes.
Not infrequently, the high-speed showdown turns into painful and momentous seriousness: Since January 2019 and until April 2020, three people have died nationwide in the races, two of them bystanders in a night-time crash in Stuttgart's city center and one in Gerlingen.
There, two young men are said to have competed in a car race in November.
One of the vehicles came off the road, crashed into a garden wall and remained on its side, the 18-year-old passenger died.
Another 21 people have been injured in the races of the past two years.
