Austria: Mass tests after corona outbreak
Authorities have responded to a corona outbreak in the popular Upper Austrian tourist town of St. Wolfgang with hundreds of tests.
The number of confirmed cases rose to 48, according to the state authorities in Linz.
More than 100 results were still pending in the evening.
Many of those infected are young interns in tourism companies, but at least one holidaymaker has also tested positive.
Residents, guests and tourism staff were asked to stay in their accommodation on Saturday evening.
The curfew was set at 11 p.m.
"There are cancellations and cancellations here and there" of bookings, said the head of the Wolfgangsee Tourism Association, Hans Wieser, to the dpa.
Occasional guests had also left early.
St. Wolfgang is the most important tourist destination in Upper Austria, with more than 400,000 overnight stays last year.
In a normal season, around a third of the guests are Germans.
The first infections became public knowledge on Friday.
The head of the district authority, Alois Lanz, defended on Saturday the behaviour of the interns, who had celebrated in several restaurants and could have become infected there.
"We all enjoyed doing that in our youth," he told radio station 1.
However, two bars were closed on Friday to prevent further infections.
The tourism board launched an information campaign to raise awareness among young employees about the dangers of COVID-19.
From Saturday, hundreds of employees, holidaymakers and locals were tested.
In addition, all guests who were in St. Wolfgang from 15 July were contacted.
The outbreak brings back memories of the Austrian ski and party resort of Ischgl in Tyrol, which was a centre of corona spread throughout Europe in the early stages of the pandemic.
Overall, more than 1500 people in Austria are currently infected with the virus.
The main areas of new infections are Vienna and Upper Austria.
Premier League: Man United and Chelsea qualified for Champions League
London (dpa) - The English football record champions Manchester United returns to the Champions League after a year's absence.
The Red Devils secured third place in the Premier League with a 2-0 (0-0) win over direct rivals Leicester City on the final day of the Premier League.
The Foxes now have to content themselves with the Europa League, because Chelsea FC passed by and qualified for the premier class in fourth place.
In the fight against relegation, Aston Villa could cheer.
Manchester United took the lead through a penalty kick from Bruno Fernandes (71st minute).
After a red card for Leicester City in added time, Jesse Lingard (90th + 8) scored the final score.
Chelsea, FC Bayern's opponent in the Champions League round of 16, won 2-0 (2-0) against Wolverhampton Wanderers thanks to Mason Mount (45th + 1) and Olivier Giroud (45th + 4).
"That means a lot to me," said coach Frank Lampard, who is also in the FA Cup final against Arsenal in his first season as Chelsea coach.
Chelsea's win over Wolverhampton also benefited Tottenham Hotspur, who moved past Wolves with a meager 1-1 (1-0) at Crystal Palace to start sixth in the Europa League.
Aston Villa won the long-distance duel with Watford FC and AFC Bournemouth, but had to shiver for a long time at West Ham United.
The late lead of Jack Grealish (84th) immediately equalized Andrey Yarmolenko (85th).
But the 1: 1 (0: 0) was enough, because Watford lost 2: 3 (1: 3) at Arsenal.
The club, which sacked three coaches during the season, is relegated after five premier league years.
Just like Bournemouth, which could not save itself by a 3: 1 (2: 1) at FC Everton.
In the end, one point was missing.
Liverpool FC, who have been English champions since the end of June, secured a club record with a 3-1 (1-1) win at Newcastle United.
99 points is the highest the Reds have ever scored in a football season.
Coach Jürgen Klopp and his team narrowly missed the points record in English football.
Manchester City holds the record with 100 points in the 2017 / 18 season.
After the Newcastle lead in the first minute, Virgil van Dijk (38th), Divock Origi (59th) and Sadio Mané (89th) turned the game on Sunday for Liverpool.
"It has been an extraordinary season for this wonderful club," goal scorer van Dijk said after the game, "that should spur us on to defend the title.
It will be hard. ".
The Premier League bosses should also be happy in the end.
Football operations in England were suspended from 13 March to 17 June due to the coronavirus crisis.
In the meantime, there was even discussion about prematurely stopping or holding the remaining games on neutral ground.
In the end, however, the season could be played to the end without any special incidents - however, as in Germany, without spectators in the stadiums.
Arrests and violence at demonstrations against Netanyahu
The protests in Israel against Prime Minister Netanyahu are becoming increasingly violent.
During the night there were violent clashes.
The Israeli police took violent action against participants in a demonstration against the right-wing conservative Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in Jerusalem on Sunday night.
Twelve people have been arrested for participating in riots, said police spokesman Micky Rosenfeld.
The police used water cannons to disperse the rally.
According to media reports, around 6,000 people had gathered near Netanyahu's official residence on Saturday evening.
They protested against unemployment, corruption and Netanyahu's handling of the corona crisis.
The protesters beat drums, blew horns and called on Netanyahu to resign.
Participants in a counter-demonstration supporting Netanyahu were also arrested, the news website "ynet" reported.
People also demonstrated in many other places in Israel, including in front of the prime minister's private villa in the coastal city of Caesarea and in a park in Tel Aviv.
A man has been arrested near Tel Aviv on suspicion of spraying pepper spray on roadside demonstrators from a moving car, according to police.
Another man was arrested after a knife attack on a demonstrator in the south of the country.
The demonstrator was slightly injured in the neck.
In Jerusalem and Tel Aviv there have recently been several demonstrations against Netanyahu.
The rallies accompany the corruption trial against the head of government.
Recently, Netanyahu has also been criticized for his handling of the corona crisis.
Among other things, he is accused of premature relaxation and a lack of preparation for a second corona wave.
The corona crisis has hit the country's economy hard.
The unemployment rate was more than 20 percent.
The number of new coronavirus infections in Israel recently rose to record levels.
