FC Bayern Munich: Pavard injured
Munich (dpa) - The start of the hot preparation phase for the Champions League began with a setback for double winner FC Bayern.
After a short holiday and a few days of training, Hansi Flick, who has recovered "reasonably well," already has to consider after the first team training how he can rebuild his successful defense after the injury of world champion Benjamin Pavard.
The Frenchman, who has the third most minutes behind captain Manuel Neuer and midfielder Joshua Kimmich, suffered a ligament injury to his left foot and is in danger of missing crucial premier class duels.
In Munich's dirty weather, the right-back broke off a training game and was driven off the course with a golf cart.
How long the unrestricted regular player has to pause in the fight for the title is open.
The 24-year-old is unlikely to be able to play in the second leg against Chelsea on 8 August, but can hope for the final tournament starting on 12 August in Lisbon.
The Bavarians do not want to be stopped by the mishap from the training on Sunday.
In his personal triple formula, Flick named the three attributes he wants to see from his stars on the way to Portugal's capital.
Quality, intensity and concentration should show his victory-hungry title collectors in the ideally following 28 days until the premier class final on 23 August.
"We have mastered the compulsory tasks with the championship and trophy simply outstandingly.
Now we have to create something special, "said Flick.
Until the Munich team can deal with the final tournament and before that a training camp in the Algarve, the obligation to play in the last 16 against FC Chelsea is pending.
After the 3: 0 in the first leg before the Corona break, the Londoners should not become a Bayern nightmare again in the home arena as in the lost "Finale dahoam" in 2012.
"We have to go through the door first.
We want to win, create good conditions and gain confidence with a good game, "demanded Flick.
A test for the tuning-up is on Friday against Olympique Marseille.
With a long speech, Flick had sworn his stars, who had 13 days vacation after the double, to a unique August.
He welcomed 31 players to Säbener Strasse, including the new players around high-end shopping Leroy Sané, who met all his new colleagues on the pitch for the first time after his move from Manchester City.
"Leroy, like all newcomers, has fitted in well," Flick said.
But instead of talking about the new season, when Sané & Co. are no longer just allowed to train, Flick preferred to talk about the current title project of the German series champion.
After days of individual and small-group training, the Londoners are now training in team strength, who, unlike the Flick ensemble, are in the rhythm of the game.
After that, Munich could face a quarter-final against FC Barcelona and Lionel Messi, in the semi-finals Real Madrid, Manchester City or Juventus Turin are possible opponents.
A path to the finals in Lisbon "is not that easy," stressed the head coach, who can rely on the services of his new assistant Miroslav Klose in training from Tuesday.
The World Cup record scorer Klose and Flick know from many a joint tournament preparation, what is particularly important in the 0-to-100 tuning.
Working with his current team is "a pleasure," praised Flick.
The "focus on winning" is an impressive trait of his team.
The tournament with nine-team teams was also ambitious on Sunday.
All of the top performers were there, including Thiago and defender David Alaba, whose stay beyond the premier class season is not assured.
Formula 1 needs a special rule to crown its world champion
Since it is not possible to race on the required number of continents, the FIA has to improvise to award the World Championship titles.
All American races were cancelled.
Racing calendar is becoming more concrete
The racing calendar of the current Formula One season continues to take shape.
In addition to the ten Grand Prix confirmed so far, three more racetracks were added during the week.
In October, the Nürburgring in Germany and Portimo in Portugal are to be raced.
On the first of November, Lewis Hamilton and Co. will fight for World Championship points at the traditional Italian race track in Imola.
This means that the 2020 race calendar currently includes 13 races.
"We are pleased that we continue to make great progress in finalizing our plans for the 2020 season," said Formula One boss Chase Carey.
In total, 15 to 18 races in the premier class of motorsport are to be completed in this extraordinary season.
Formula 1 wants to close its season in Asia.
The final race calendar will be fixed and published in the coming weeks.
According to media reports, appearances in Vietnam and Malaysia could take place at the end of November ahead of the already officially targeted races in Bahrain and Abu Dhabi in December.
Regulations require races on three continents
However, the Formula 1 regulations require at least races on three continents for the awarding of the World Championship.
Even if, as currently planned, only two continents will be raced, there should be a world champion.
The FIA will use a special rule to award the titles, citing "exceptional circumstances" due to the coronavirus pandemic.
The traditional season start in Australia in March had to be cancelled at short notice due to the looming corona crisis.
A return to the continent later this year is not an issue.
In addition, Formula 1 will not be in America this year.
Cancellation meets with criticism in Brazil
Due to the tense corona situation, the races in Canada, the USA, Mexico and Brazil will not take place.
"We look forward to being with them again next season," Carey said.
The cancellation of the American races was criticized especially in Brazil: "The cancellation did not come as a surprise to us, but we cannot accept the reasons for it," said Tamas Rohonyi, promoter of the Grand Prix in So Paulo.
The number of infections in the So Paulo region is significantly lower than in other regions of Brazil.
The concerns of some teams about not wanting to race in Brazil would not justify a cancellation.
They are prepared for the required security measures.
Greta Thunberg: Evil eye against Donald Trump went around the world
Greta Thunberg spoke about her meeting with US President Donald Trump.
Greta Thunberg was a guest on Stephen Colbert's famous latenight show via video link and revealed in an interview what she had in mind when she met Donald Trump.
Climate activist Greta Thunberg was a guest on a popular US late-night show via video link.
Among other things, she told of her struggle against the powerful of the world.
The teenager also spoke about her famous "evil eye" during her encounter with Donald Trump.
New York City - Over the past two years, climate activist Greta Thunberg has attracted attention with her tireless commitment to the "Fridays For Future" movement.
Now she spoke on a well-known latenight show about her plans for the future as well as her meeting with US President Donald Trump at the UN climate summit last year.
Latenight host Stephen Colbert welcomed 17-year-old Thunberg to your show on Tuesday and conducted a lengthy interview with the Swede.
She spoke not only about her fight against climate change, but also about her conflict with the world's powerful.
"There are some things that surprised me," she said.
"How far people go to shift the focus away from the climate crisis," she said.
"Everything from organized hate campaigns to threats just because a group of children take to the streets," she said.
Heads of state and political leaders who scoff at her on social media, or even try to silence her, find her "funny" because the reactions show her "because they have no other answer.".
It became particularly interesting at the end of the interview, when Greta Thunberg was asked about a well-known scene in which she gave US President Trump an angry look.
At the 2019 UN Climate Summit in New York, for which the activist sailed across the Atlantic, her expressive gaze was caught by the cameras and has since been seen by countless people on the Internet.
The short clip turned into a GIF, an animated image that ultimately became one of the most widely used images for Trump opponents.
But what did the 17-year-old think about the American president at that moment?
To Stephen Colbert's relatively open question, she replied only briefly and dryly: "To be honest, I don't think it needs any further explanation.".
The experienced satirist Colbert had probably not reckoned with the quick-witted answer and briefly disappeared from the picture, laughing.
With her "How dare you?" speech on the principles of climate protection, she was remembered by many at the climate conference.
Ex-Dortmunder Immobile with three-pack for Lazio Rome
